ibbs Racing\n| Chevrolet|| 29.338||167.619\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 29\n|5\n|{{Sortname|Terry|Labonte}}\n| Hendrick Motorsports|| Chevrolet|| 29.382||167.368\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 30\n| 31||{{Sortname|Robby|Gordon}}\n|[[Richard Childress Racing]]\n| Chevrolet||29.423\n|167.135\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 31\n|32\n|{{Sortname|Ricky|Craven}}\n|[[PPI Motorsports]]\n| Pontiac||29.425\n|167.123\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 32\n| 30||{{Sortname|Jeff|Green|Jeff Green (racing driver)}}\n|Richard Childress Racing\n| Chevrolet|| 29.462||166.913\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 33\n|29\n|{{Sortname|Kevin|Harvick}}\n|Richard Childress Racing\n| Chevrolet|| 29.463||166.908\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 34\n| 0||{{Sortname|Jack|Sprague}}\n|[[Stewart-Haas Racing|Haas CNC Racing]]\n|Pontiac\n|29.484\n|166.789\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 35\n| 1||{{Sortname|Steve|Park}}\n|Dale Earnhardt, Inc.\n|Chevrolet\n|29.498\n|166.710\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 36\n| 88||{{Sortname|Dale|Jarrett}}||Robert Yates Racing\n| Ford|| 29.554||166.394\n|-\n| colspan=\"7\" |<center>'''Provisional'''</center>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 37\n|99\n|{{Sortname|Jeff|Burton}}\n|Roush Racing\n| Ford||29.637\n|165.928\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 38\n|25\n|{{Sortname|Joe|Nemechek}}\n|Hendrick Motorsports\n| Chevrolet||29.758\n|165.253\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 39\n|21\n|{{Sortname|Ricky|Rudd}}\n|[[Wood Brothers Racing]]\n| Ford||29.592\n|166.292\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 40\n|45\n|{{Sortname|Kyle|Petty}}\n|Petty Enterprises\n| Ford|| 29.643||165.894\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 41\n|74\n|{{Sortname|Tony|Raines}}\n|[[BACE Motorsports]]\n| Chevrolet|| 29.819||164.915\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 42\n|14\n|{{Sortname|Larry|Foyt}}\n|[[A. J. Foyt Enterprises|A. J. Foyt Racing]]\n|Dodge\n| 29.931||164.298\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 43\n|57\n|{{Sortname|Brett|Bodine}}\n|[[CLR Racing]]\n| Ford|| 29.657||165.816\n|-class=\"sortbottom\"\n|colspan=\"8\"|{{center|{{small|''Source:<ref>{{cite web|title=Race Lineup: Carolina Dodge Dealers 400|url=http://www.nascar.com/races/wc/2003/5/data/lineup.html|publisher=NASCAR|date=March 2003|accessdate=September 13, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030320015906/http://www.nascar.com/races/wc/2003/5/data/lineup.html|archivedate=March 20, 2003|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Starting lineup \u2013 Carolina Dodge Dealers 400|url=https://www.crash.net/nascar/news/87270/1/starting-lineup-carolina-dodge-dealers-400|publisher=Crash|date=March 14, 2003|accessdate=January 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>''}}}}\n|}\n\n==Race==\nLive television coverage of the race in the United States on [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] began at 12:30 [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern Time]] ([[UTC\u221205:00]]).<ref name=\"event\" /> Around the start of the race, the weather was cool and overcast,<ref name=\"DPRace\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dailypress.com/sports/motorracing/dp-70070sy0mar17,0,3919558.story?coll=dp-sports-auto|title=A finish to remember: Craven beats Busch by 0.002 seconds|last=Pearce|first=Al|date=March 17, 2003|work=[[Daily Press (Virginia)|Daily Press]]|accessdate=September 11, 2019|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030402012546/http://www.dailypress.com/sports/motorracing/dp-70070sy0mar17,0,3919558.story?coll=dp-sports-auto|archivedate=April 2, 2003}}</ref> with the air temperature {{Convert|63|F|C|abbr=on}}. Harold King, a board member of Darlington Raceway, began pre-race ceremonies with an [[invocation]].<ref name=FOXRace>{{cite AV media |last1=Joy|first1=Mike|author-link1=Mike Joy|last2=Waltrip|first2=Darrell|author-link2=Darrell Waltrip|last3=McReynolds|first3=Larry |author-link3=Larry McReynolds|date=March 16, 2003 |title=NASCAR on Fox |medium=Television production |time= |location=Darlington, South Carolina |publisher=Fox Broadcasting Company}}</ref> Ann Benson, president of music at [[Columbia College (South Carolina)|Columbia College]] in [[Columbia, South Carolina]], performed the [[The Star-Spangled Banner|national anthem]], and [[Mark Sanford]], the [[Governor of South Carolina]], commanded the drivers to start their engines.<ref name=\"event\" /> During the [[Parade lap|pace laps]], Busch and Waltrip moved to the rear of the field because of their engine change and switch to a back-up car.<ref name=\"RR400\" /> [[Grip (auto racing)|Grip]] was difficult to locate and any advantage that drivers gained was minimal.<ref name=\"NASCAROralRace\">{{cite web|last=Albert|first=Zack|title=Too Tough to Forget|url=https://www.nascar.com/long-form/darlington-finish-oral-history-zack-albert/|publisher=NASCAR|format=[https://www.nascar.com/long-form/darlington-finish-oral-history-zack-albert/ page 1], [https://www.nascar.com/long-form/darlington-finish-oral-history-zack-albert-2/ page 2]|date=March 15, 2018|accessdate=September 11, 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315191726/https://www.nascar.com/long-form/darlington-finish-oral-history-zack-albert/|archive-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nNewman passed Sadler for the lead in the first turn,<ref name=\"SMRace\" /> which he held until Sadler retook it on the approach to the same corner at the beginning of lap two.<ref name=\"CORace\">{{cite news|last=Poole|first=David|title=Craven slips past Busch at Darlington|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A98821203/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=7f647f0e|work=Charlotte Observer|agency=Knight Ridder/Tribune News Service|date=March 16, 2003|accessdate=September 11, 2019|page=K6276|via=Gale General OneFile|url-access=subscription|url-status=live}}</ref> On the third lap, Nadeau overtook Newman for second.<ref name=\"FrontstretchRace\">{{cite web|last=Ames|first=Vanessa|title=I thought Bristol was next week \u2013 A detailed Carolina Dodge Dealers 400 recap|url=http://www.frontstretch.com/backend/display.php?article=116|publisher=Frontstrech|date=March 16, 2003|accessdate=September 11, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030516172552/http://www.frontstretch.com/backend/display.php?article=116|archivedate=May 16, 2003|url-status=dead}}</ref> Three laps later,<ref name=\"SMRace\">{{cite web|last=Cady|first=Matthew|title=Craven wins Dodge Dealers 400|url=http://www.speedwaymedia.com/Articles/031703Cady.asp|publisher=SpeedwayMedia|date=March 17, 2003|accessdate=September 11, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030401064343/http://www.speedwaymedia.com/Articles/031703Cady.asp|archivedate=April 1, 2003|url-status=dead}}</ref> Nadeau lost control of his car heading into the first corner,<ref name=\"CORace\" /> and spun 360 degrees.<ref name=\"event\" /> He avoided contact with a trackside wall and another car.<ref name=\"FrontstretchRace\" /> Drivers behind him drove onto the [[Glossary of motorsport terms#A|apron]] to avoid a collision;<ref name=\"SMRace\" /><ref name=\"CORace\" /> [[Jamie McMurray]] made contact with Kenseth, causing the latter to spin, and bringing out the first [[Racing flags#Yellow flag|yellow caution flag]].<ref name=\"event\" /> Some drivers who had tight-handling cars elected to make [[pit stop]]s for tires during the caution.<ref name=\"CORace\" /><ref name=\"FrontstretchRace\" /> Sadler maintained the lead at the lap 10 restart,<ref name=\"RR400\" /> followed by Gordon.<ref name=\"FrontstretchRace\" /> Four laps later, [[Jack Sprague]] spun 360 degrees on the exit of turn four, prompting the second caution.<ref name=\"event\" /><ref name=\"SMRace\" /> Under caution, those drivers who remained on the track during the first caution, including Sadler, made pit stops.<ref name=\"CORace\" />\n\n[[File:Daleearnhardtjr.jpg|alt=A man in his late twenties wearing black sunglasses and a red and black racing suit adorned with sponsors' logos|left|thumb|upright|[[Dale Earnhardt Jr.]] ''(pictured in 2002)'' led a total of 91 laps, more than any other driver]]\n\nSpencer did not make a pit stop and led at the restart on lap 17, followed by Earnhardt, Nadeau, [[John Andretti]], and Green. On the following lap, Earnhardt's new tires helped him pass Spencer for the lead going into the third turn.<ref name=\"CORace\" /><ref name=\"FrontstretchRace\" /> Lap 23 saw the third caution:<ref name=\"RR400\" /> Johnson made contact with Marlin, who was sent veering into an outside barrier on the backstretch. A cut tire disabled the steering on Marlin's vehicle on the run to turn one, and he crashed against a wall.<ref name=\"CORace\" /> This caused a chain-reaction accident involving Labonte, Sprague, Todd Bodine, Harvick, [[Robby Gordon]], and Raines. The latter three continued driving with aerodynamic deficiencies to their cars. Every driver besides Jarrett and Jeff Gordon made pit stops during the caution.<ref name=\"FrontstretchRace\" /> Jarrett led the field back to racing speed at the lap 29 restart.<ref name=\"RR400\" /> On the 32nd lap, Earnhardt overtook Gordon and then Jarrett to return to the lead.<ref name=\"FrontstretchRace\" /> The fourth caution was necessitated on lap 33 when Jeff Burton in ninth position had an engine failure,<ref name=\"SMRace\" /> which obscured Stewart's vision and caused him to ram into Burton's car.<ref name=\"event\" /> Jarrett and Jeff Gordon made pit stops for tires under caution.<ref name=\"FrontstretchRace\" />\n\nEarnhardt remained the leader from Nadeau and Spencer at the restart on lap 40. Two laps later, Stewart struck a trackside barrier; he continued without major damage to his car.<ref name=\"FrontstretchRace\" /> Earnhardt led Nadeau by five seconds by the 50th lap, while Martin and his [[Roush Fenway Racing|Roush Racing]] teammate Busch had advanced to third and fourth places.<ref name=\"CORace\" /> On lap 68, the fifth caution came out after Newman and Ward Burton raced each other in turn two. Burton drifted into the side of Newman's car and both cars spun without a collision against a barrier. Track officials used dry blowers to remove debris.<ref name=\"event\" /> Some drivers made pit stops for tires during the caution. Earnhardt retained the lead from Martin and Nadeau at the restart on lap 75.<ref name=\"FrontstretchRace\" /> Twelve laps later a fractured oil casing forced Nadeau to enter pit road, and he dropped out of contention for a strong result.<ref name=\"CORace\" /> Earnhardt established a lengthy advantage over Martin until slower traffic impeded him and allowed Martin to execute a pass for the first position on the 117th lap.<ref name=\"CORace\" /><ref name=\"FrontstretchRace\" />\n\nGreen flag pit stops commenced on lap 121. Busch attempted to enter pit road eight laps later; he missed the entrance and completed one extra lap on the circuit as he remained on the same lap as the leader.<ref name=\"SMRace\" /><ref name=\"FrontstretchRace\" /> On the same lap, Gordon passed Earnhardt for second place. Martin made his pit stop on the 132nd lap. He relinquished the lead to Gordon for a single lap. After the pit stops Martin regained the lead, with Gordon four seconds behind in second, and Kenseth third.<ref name=\"CORace\" /> By lap 169, Sadler had overtaken Kenseth and Gordon to advance to second position. The second round of green flag pit stops commenced on lap 185. Drivers who made pit stops hoping to advance their positions did not succeed, however, because a sixth caution was waved on lap 191.<ref name=\"FrontstretchRace\" /> The right front corner of Spencer's vehicle came into contact with Andretti's left-rear wheel, causing the latter to sustain a [[flat tire]].<ref name=\"SMRace\" /> Andretti veered towards an inside barrier on the frontstretch and sustained damage to his car. Andretti was uninjured.<ref name=\"event\" />\n\nSome drivers, including Martin, made pit stops during the caution. Gordon led the field at the lap 197 restart.<ref name=\"FrontstretchRace\" /> Martin made a brisk getaway to overtake Sadler and reclaim second position.<ref name=\"CORace\" /> Just as pit stop strategy was about affect the final result,<ref name=\"FrontstretchRace\" /> officials noticed debris between the third and fourth turns and waved the seventh caution flag on lap 237.<ref name=\"event\" /> Several teams called their drivers into the pit lane for their final scheduled pit stops. Gordon exited pit road in first place,<ref name=\"CORace\" /> as a mechanic for Martin's car dropped a left front [[lug nut]], which required Martin to stop again.<ref name=\"SMRace\" /> He fell to eleventh position.<ref name=\"FrontstretchRace\" /> The race restarted on the 242nd lap,<ref name=\"RR400\" /> with Gordon ahead of Sadler, Busch, Craven, and Blaney.<ref name=\"SMRace\" /> Busch, whose [[power steering]] began to cut out from lap 243,<ref name=\"DPRace\" /> passed Sadler for second place shortly after, and he began to duel Gordon for the lead. Sadler subsequently got involved, as Craven and Blaney used the battle to draw closer to them.<ref name=\"FrontstretchRace\" />\n\nOn lap 269, Gordon grazed the wall at turn two, which allowed Sadler to challenge him; his momentum was disrupted as he and Gordon went onto the backstretch.<ref name=\"CORace\" /> Busch drew alongside the pair,<ref name=\"AJCRace\">{{cite news|url=http://www.accessatlanta.com/ajc/sports/0303/17nascar.html|title=Craven wins by inches over Busch|last=Minter|first=Rick|date=March 16, 2003|work=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|accessdate=September 11, 2019|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030411211226/http://www.accessatlanta.com/ajc/sports/0303/17nascar.html|archivedate=April 11, 2003}}</ref> and steered to the bottom lane in turn three to take the lead.<ref name=\"SpeedRace\">{{cite web|last=Blake|first=Ben|title=One of the Best: Craven Beats Busch in Thriller|url=http://www.speedtv.com/articles/auto/nascar/5516/|publisher=Speed|date=March 16, 2003|accessdate=September 11, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030413055022/http://www.speedtv.com/articles/auto/nascar/5516/|archivedate=April 13, 2003|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"DBNJRace\">{{cite news|last=Kelly|first=Goodwin|title=No denying Craven: No. 32 bumps off Busch at line|url=http://www.news-journalonline.com/NewsJournalOnline/Speed/Headlines/speedWC1031703.htm|work=The Daytona Beach News-Journal|date=March 17, 2003|accessdate=September 11, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030626132241/http://www.news-journalonline.com/NewsJournalOnline/Speed/Headlines/speedWC1031703.htm|archivedate=June 26, 2003|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"ESPN10YearsOn\">{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/racing/nascar/cup/story/_/id/9262583/nascar-door-door-darlington-2003-finish-epic|title=Darlington 2003 finish still resonates|last=Smith|first=Marty|date=May 10, 2013|publisher=ESPN|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323133659/https://www.espn.com/racing/nascar/cup/story/_/id/9262583/nascar-door-door-darlington-2003-finish-epic|archive-date=March 23, 2020|accessdate=September 11, 2019}}</ref> Gordon and Sadler struck a trackside wall on lap 273, allowing Craven to pass the duo and move into second five laps later.<ref name=\"SMRace\" /><ref name=\"SpeedRace\" /> Sadler and Gordon then slowed with damage to their vehicles' [[Toe (automotive)|toes]].<ref name=\"MCOMRace\">{{cite web|url=https://www.motorsport.com/nascar-cup/news/craven-wins-wild-finish-at-darlington/117548/|title=Craven wins wild finish at Darlington|date=March 16, 2003|publisher=[[motorsport.com]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323134132/https://www.motorsport.com/nascar-cup/news/craven-wins-wild-finish-at-darlington/117548/|archive-date=March 23, 2020|accessdate=September 11, 2019}}</ref> Craven, who had conserved the wear on his tires, had his crew chief Scott Miller read him his lap times and learnt he was faster than Busch;<ref name=\"NASCAROralRace\" /> Craven slowed in turn four to avoid rear tire [[Burnout (vehicle)|burnout]].<ref name=\"ESPN10YearsOn\" /> With a three-second lead it appeared that Busch would win comfortably,<ref name=\"FrontstretchRace\" /> but his [[Spotter (auto racing)|spotter]] informed him over the radio that Craven was drawing nearer.<ref name=\"ESPN10YearsOn\" /> On the 283rd lap, Gordon drifted up the track, and hit a wall.<ref name=\"event\" /> Kenny Wallace hit Gordon's car,<ref name=\"event\" /> prompting the latter to enter pit road and retire from the event.<ref name=\"FrontstretchRace\" />\n\n[[File:Ricky Craven 1997.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Ricky Craven]] ''(pictured in 1997)'' won the race by two-thousands of a second, the joint-closest finish in NASCAR Cup Series history]]\n\nWith ten laps to go, Busch's power steering failed,<ref name=\"MCOMRace\" /> numbing his arms,<ref name=\"RTRace\">{{cite news|url=http://www1.roanoke.com/sports/racing/8497.html|title=Craven bumps, grinds to narrowest of wins|last=Long|first=Dustin|date=March 17, 2003|work=[[The Roanoke Times]]|accessdate=September 11, 2019|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030422114645/http://www1.roanoke.com/sports/racing/8497.html|archivedate=April 22, 2003}}</ref> reducing his stamina,<ref name=\"RTDRace\">{{cite news|last=Ryan|first=Nate|title=Picture this: Craven wins in photo finish He holds off Busch in last-lap shootout|url=http://timesdispatch.com/sports/auto/MGBRKK6XDDD.html|work=Richmond Times-Dispatch|date=March 17, 2003|accessdate=September 11, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030413121343/http://timesdispatch.com/sports/auto/MGBRKK6XDDD.html|archivedate=April 13, 2003|url-status=dead}}</ref> and making his car more difficult to handle.<ref name=\"SMRace\" /> On lap 289, Craven began to gain on Busch, with Blaney [[Drafting (aerodynamics)|drafting]] him.<ref name=\"FrontstretchRace\" /> He caught Busch on the 291st lap;<ref name=\"SMRace\" /> Craven steered left to attempt a pass before turn one a lap later,<ref name=\"DBNJRace\" /> which Busch responded to with a blocking maneuver popularized by [[Dale Earnhardt]] in that corner, a move the former anticipated.<ref name=\"NASCAROralRace\" /> Busch maintained the lead on the backstretch,<ref name=\"FrontstretchRace\" /> as Craven's car got loose because he could not remove his hands from the steering wheel and drive towards the barrier.<ref name=\"NASCAROralRace\" /> Craven followed Busch in turns three and four,<ref name=\"SMRace\" /> and went to the inside of him at the beginning of lap 292.<ref name=\"RTRace\" /> The two made contact into turn one;<ref name=\"RTDRace\" /> Craven slowed as Busch steered to the inside in turn two,<ref name=\"SMRace\" /> after he was put towards a wall. Busch used his car's front bumper in a [[Bump and run (auto racing)|bump and run maneuver]] on Craven to regain the lead.<ref name=\"CORace\" /><ref name=\"AJCRace\" /><ref name=\"SpeedRace\" />\n\nBusch opened up an advantage of about four-tenths of a second as he and Craven began the final lap.<ref name=\"SMRace\" /> Craven followed Busch through the first and second corner as part of a plan to challenge Busch at the exit of the final turn.<ref name=\"NASCAROralRace\" /> As Busch perceived this as the ideal situation, he had no plan for taking the victory; Craven on the outside was faster through turns three and four because Busch had to fight to regain control of his car.<ref name=\"ESPN10YearsOn\" /> Between turns three and four,<ref name=\"DPRace\" /> Busch [[Wheelspin|spun his tires lightly]],<ref name=\"AJCRace\" /> and could not steer to block Craven on the inside heading into the frontstretch.<ref name=\"ESPN10YearsOn\" /><ref name=\"DPRace\" /> Craven drew alongside Busch at the exit of turn four;<ref name=\"AJCRace\" /> both drivers got loose without slowing,<ref name=\"NASCAROralRace\" /><ref name=\"ESPN10YearsOn\" /> and clattered into each other several times in the final {{Convert|300|yd|m|abbr=on}},<ref name=\"AJCRace\" /> with smoke emitting from their tires.<ref name=\"DPRace\" />\n\nCraven earned his second career win, beating Busch by two-thousands of a second (about {{Convert|4|in|ft|abbr=on}}),<ref name=\"CORace\" /><ref name=\"ESPN10YearsOn\" /> then the closest finish in NASCAR Cup Series history since the introduction of electronic scoring in the [[1993 NASCAR Winston Cup Series|1993 season]].{{refn|group=N|name=Finish|The record was equalled eight years later by [[Jimmie Johnson]] in the [[2011 Aaron's 499]] at [[Talladega Superspeedway]].<ref name=FinishGap/>}}<ref name=\"DBNJRace\" /><ref name=\"FinishGap\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedrive.com/accelerator/19322/nascars-busch-and-craven-recall-darlington-finish-15-years-later|title=NASCAR's Busch and Craven Recall Darlington Finish 15 Years Later|last=Vincent|first=Amanda|date=March 16, 2018|publisher=The Drive|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323134023/https://www.thedrive.com/accelerator/19322/nascars-busch-and-craven-recall-darlington-finish-15-years-later|archive-date=March 23, 2020|access-date=September 13, 2019}}</ref> Blaney placed third, his best career finish.<ref name=\"DBNJRace\" /> Martin, Waltrip, Earnhardt, Sadler, Kenseth, Elliott, and Stewart completed the top ten.<ref name=\"SpeedRace\" /> There were seven yellow flag cautions, and fifteen lead changes amongst eleven different drivers during the race. Earnhardt's 91 laps led was the most of any driver. Craven led once for a single lap. The race took 3 hours, 10 minutes, and 16 seconds; and Craven's average winning speed was {{Convert|126.214|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"RR400\" />\n\n===Post-race===\nAfter crossing the finish line, Craven corrected his car, and on the way back to pit road, asked his crew who had won the race.<ref name=\"AJCRace\" /> Leaving turn two,<ref name=\"SpeedRace\" /> he glanced to his left to read the scoring pylon informing drivers and spectators of the finishing positions, and learnt he had succeed.<ref name=\"ESPN10YearsOn\" /> He ventured to victory lane,<ref name=\"ESPN10YearsOn\" /> to celebrate his victory in front of a crowd of 55,000 spectators;<ref name=\"AJCRace\" /> the win earned him $172,150.<ref name=\"RR400\" /> Busch, known as \"a fiery competitor\",<ref name=\"NASCAROralRace\" /> went to shake Craven's hand in an act of sportsmanship.<ref name=\"ESPN10YearsOn\" />\n\nCraven commented on the win, \"It's the most fun I've ever had in my life. This is exactly what you dream of. It will probably never happen again, but it's the perfect way to win a race at the perfect track. I have always wanted to win a race here\",<ref name=\"RTDRace\" /> and, \"This is exactly what you dream of. It will probably never happen again, but it's the perfect way to win a race at the perfect track.\"<ref name=\"DBNJRace\" /> Busch was complimentary of the finish, \"I can't wait to go see him. That was the coolest finish I've ever seen, and I'm glad I got to be a part of it. This is something where we'll slap high-fives and drink a couple beers to later on.\"<ref name=\"RTDRace\" /> Blaney spoke of the potential significance over his third-place result, \"It's huge. I felt like I could race with these guys, it's just tough to get everything put together. I feel like we've got a team that's running well. Everything is flowing pretty good. We're not changing much with these cars. They're fast off the truck and [[Bootie Barker|Bootie]] [Barker, Blaney's crew chief] has the whole team energized and doing a great job.\"<ref name=\"MCOMRace\" />\n\nAfter the race, Johnson and his crew chief [[Chad Knaus]] were ordered to report to meet Cup Series director [[John Darby (NASCAR official)|John Darby]] in an office in NASCAR's hauler to explain the collision with Marlin early on.<ref name=\"CORace\" /><ref name=MARJOH>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nascar.com/2003/news/headlines/wc/03/19/jjohnson_smarlin/index.html|title=Johnson admits fault for crash at Darlington|last=Rodman|first=Dave|date=March 19, 2003|publisher=NASCAR|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030814011718/http://www.nascar.com/2003/news/headlines/wc/03/19/jjohnson_smarlin/index.html|archive-date=August 14, 2003|access-date=September 13, 2019}}</ref> Marlin said a slower car required him to reduce his pace,<ref name=\"MCOMRace\" /> and did not believe neither he nor Johnson were responsible for causing the accident, \"It was just racing. I've never seen so many people racing this hard so early, like there were just 10 laps left, especially at a place like this where you need to be patient.\"<ref name=\"CORace\" /> Johnson later admitted he was responsible for causing the accident, saying, \"We just had a conversation with John Darby and looked at some videos. We discussed it (and) we all agreed that it was just a racing incident. I just lost some traction off of Turn 4 and ran out of race track and pinched the No. 40 (Marlin) into the wall and crashed him and myself. It was just a racing mistake on my part.\"<ref name=MARJOH/>\n\nEarnhardt, who finished sixth and led more laps than any other driver, said an error with the installation of a lug nut prevented him from challenging for the victory, \"This [Darlington] has really been an Achilles heel for us in the past. I feel real confident about this run today. I'm pretty happy. This is a tough track and it's hard to like. You know what I mean? It's like you can't live with it and you can't live without it, I'll tell you that.\"<ref name=\"MCOMRace\" /> After his eighth-place finish, Kenseth spoke of his relief the collision with McMurray on lap six had not damaged his car's toe-in, \"Eighth was great for us today - even if we weren't as beat up as we are. As bad as we ran the last couple times here, finishing eighth is really good.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nascar.com/2003/news/headlines/wc/03/16/mkenseth_leader/index.html|title=Kenseth brings wounded car home eighth|last=Smith|first=Marty|date=March 17, 2003|publisher=NASCAR|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030401225834/http://www.nascar.com/2003/news/headlines/wc/03/16/mkenseth_leader/index.html|archive-date=April 1, 2003|access-date=September 13, 2019}}</ref> Gordon admitted he was fault for the collision on lap 273 that led to a reduction of his car's performance, and Sadler said he had committed \"a stupid driving mistake\" by following and heavily pressuring the former, and making the same driver error simultaneously.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A98906807/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=102c94d5|title=Gordon's Mistakes Shows He's Fallable|last=Long|first=Dustin|date=March 18, 2003|work=[[News & Record]]|access-date=September 13, 2019|page=C1|via=Gale OneFile: News|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nMedia reaction to the race was positive. [[Robin Miller (journalist)|Robin Miller]] of [[ESPN]] called the final two laps a sample of \"what auto racing is all about. Two guys gassing, gouging and grinding to the checkered flag \u2013 damn the consequences\" and the duel of Craven and Busch reminded him of a battle between [[Rick Mears]] and [[Gordon Johncock]] for the win in the last ten laps of the [[1982 Indianapolis 500]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/rpm/2003/0317/1525176.html|title=Craven, Busch duel a classic|last=Miller|first=Robin|authorlink=Robin Miller (journalist)|date=March 17, 2003|publisher=ESPN|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030403225512/http://espn.go.com/rpm/2003/0317/1525176.html|archive-date=April 3, 2003|access-date=September 13, 2019}}</ref> Writing for the ''[[Daily Press (Virginia)|Daily Press]]'', Al Pearce spoke of \"a marvelous stock car race\",<ref name=\"DPRace\" /> ''[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]''<nowiki/>'s Rick Minter declared \"the racing gods smiled on the old track\" after Darlington Raceway was under threat of removal from the NASCAR Cup Series,<ref name=\"AJCRace\" /> and David Poole of ''[[The Charlotte Observer]]'' stated it was \"electrifying\" and the conclusion was \"the kind of finish people will be talking about for years.\"<ref name=\"CORace\" /> In December 2009, the event was voted \"the top NASCAR race of the decade\" by the media.<ref name=\"LA2009BestRace\">{{cite news|url=https://latimesblogs.latimes.com/sports_blog/2009/12/ricky-craven-wins-nascars-top-race-of-the-decade.html|title=Ricky Craven's win at Darlington named NASCAR's top race of the decade|date=December 21, 2009|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=September 11, 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091225230809/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/sports_blog/2009/12/ricky-craven-wins-nascars-top-race-of-the-decade.html|archive-date=December 25, 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe race result kept Kenseth with 703 points in the lead of the Drivers' Championship,<ref name=\"DBNJRace\" /><ref name=\"MCOMRace\" /> ahead of Stewart in second. Waltrip remained in third. Earnhardt gained six positions to progress to fourth, and Craven's victory elevated him from sixteenth to fifth. Busch advanced to sixth, and Blaney took over seventh. Johnson, Nemechek and Sadler rounded out the top ten drivers.<ref name=PreRacePoints/><ref name=\"DBNJRace\" /> In the Manufacturers' Championship, Ford maintained the lead with 36 points; Chevrolet, Pontiac, and Dodge followed with 31, 24 and 19 respective points with 31 races remaining in the season.<ref name=Manufacturers/>\n\n===Race results===\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n|+ Race results\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Pos\n! scope=\"col\" | Grid\n! scope=\"col\" | Car\n! scope=\"col\" | Driver\n! scope=\"col\" | Team\n! scope=\"col\" | Manufacturer\n! scope=\"col\" |{{Abbr|Laps|Laps completed}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Points\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 1\n|31\n|32\n|{{Sortname|Ricky|Craven|nolink=1}}\n|PPI Motorsports\n| Pontiac||293\n|180{{smallsup|1}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2\n|6\n| 97||{{Sortname|Kurt|Busch|nolink=1}}\n|Roush Racing\n| Ford||293\n|175{{smallsup|1}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 3\n|18\n|77\n|{{Sortname|Dave|Blaney|nolink=1}}||Jasper Motorsports\n|Ford\n| 293||165\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 4\n|27\n| 6||{{sortname|Mark|Martin|nolink=1}}\n|Roush Racing\n| Ford|| 293||165{{smallsup|1}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 5\n| 9|| 15||{{sortname|Michael|Waltrip|nolink=1}}\n|Dale Earnhardt, Inc.\n|Chevrolet\n| 293||155\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 6\n| 16|| 8||{{sortname|Dale|Earnhardt Jr.|nolink=1}}\n|Dale Earnhardt, Inc.\n| Chevrolet|| 293||160{{smallsup|2}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 7\n| 1||38\n|{{sortname|Elliott|Sadler|nolink=1}}\n|Robert Yates Racing\n|Ford\n| 293||151{{smallsup|1}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 8\n|12\n| 17||{{sortname|Matt|Kenseth|nolink=1}}\n|Roush Racing\n| Ford|| 293||142\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 9\n|25\n| 9||{{Sortname|Bill|Elliott|nolink=1}}\n|Evernham Motorsports\n| Dodge|| 293||138\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 10\n| 28|| 20||{{sortname|Tony|Stewart|nolink=1}}\n| Joe Gibbs Racing|| Chevrolet|| 293||134\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 11\n| 23|| 4||{{sortname|Mike|Skinner|nolink=1}}\n|Morgan\u2013McClure Motorsports\n|Pontiac\n| 292||130\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 12\n|17\n| 16||{{sortname|Greg|Biffle|nolink=1}}\n|Roush Racing\n| Ford|| 292||127\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 13\n| 38|| 25||{{sortname|Joe|Nemechek|nolink=1}}\n| Hendrick Motorsports||Chevrolet\n| 292||129{{smallsup|1}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 14\n| 2|| 12||{{sortname|Ryan|Nemwan|dub=Ryan Newman (racing driver)|nolink=1}}\n|Penske Racing\n| Dodge|| 292||126{{smallsup|1}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 15\n| 39|| 21||{{Sortname|Ricky|Rudd|nolink=1}}\n|Wood Brothers Racing\n| Ford||292\n|118\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 16\n| 13|| 2||{{Sortname|Rusty|Wallace|nolink=1}}\n| Penske Racing|| Dodge|| 291||115\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 17\n| 15|| 49||{{sortname|Ken|Schrader|nolink=1}}\n|BAM Racing\n| Dodge|| 291||112\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 18\n| 36|| 88||{{sortname|Dale|Jarrett|nolink=1}}\n|Robert Yates Racing\n| Ford|| 291||114{{smallsup|1}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 19\n| 32|| 30||{{sortname|Jeff|Green|nolink=1}}\n| Richard Childress Racing|| Chevrolet|| 291||106\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 20\n| 35|| 1||{{Sortname|Steve|Park|nolink=1}}||Dale Earnhardt, Inc.\n|Chevrolet\n| 291||103\